DFT Calculations. $\mathbf{1 - 3}$ and the mono THF adducts were optimized at the B3LYP/SDD/6$311 \mathrm{G}(\mathrm{d})$ level of theory as a triplet, where Ni and the halide were represented with the SDD basis set and all other atoms with 6-311G(d). One small chemical simplification of the ligand was introduced; the $t$ Bu groups on the backbone were substituted by hydrogens. The metal-ligand bond lengths and angles agree well with the crystallographic values (Tables S4 and S5), suggesting that the model is adequate. Calculated $d$-orbital splitting diagrams for $\mathbf{1}$ and $\mathbf{1} \cdot \mathrm{THF}$ are shown in Figure 6. Two singly occupied molecular orbitals (SOMOs), $d x^{2}-y^{2}$ and $d z^{2}$, are energetically wellseparated from three low-lying doubly-occupied $d$ orbitals. As is shown in Figure 7, the HOMO (in both the $\alpha$ and $\beta$ subspaces) is best described as a ligand $\pi$ orbital for both the four- and fivecoordinate species with only a small contribution from Ni (see Figure S8 for similar plots of 2 and 3). The ligand-centered HOMO is commonly observed in donor ligands with more extended $\pi$ conjugation. ${ }^{66}$\\
